Flink is a real-time stream processing engine used to process data as it arrives (not in batches).
distributed stateful stream computation engine
A stream is an infinite sequence of events (clicks, logs, transactions) processed in order as they arrive.
Very common in:

fraud detection (banking)
real-time recommendations (Netflix, Amazon)
monitoring & alerting (DevOps, AWS systems)
IoT sensor processing
Kafka stream processing pipelines

Flink architecture - 
Sources → Stream → Transformations → Sink
(Kafka)     |          |              (DB)
         Flink engine (processing)

Operators are transformations like:
         map
         filter
         keyBy
         window
         reduce

Typical stack:

Kafka → Flink → DynamoDB / Cassandra / S3

Because streams never end, Flink groups data using windows:

Types:
tumbling windows (fixed)
sliding windows (overlapping)
session windows (user activity bursts)

Windows group infinite streams into finite chunks:
         tumbling (fixed non-overlapping)
         sliding (overlapping)
         session (activity-based grouping)

Flink remembers things:
  user session
  running totals
  counters
This is called:
stateful stream processing

Event time vs Processing time
Event time: when event actually happened
Processing time: when Flink processed it
👉 Event time is more correct but harder

Watermark - A watermark is a signal that tells Flink “no more events before this timestamp are expected”, used to handle late/out-of-order events.
Why watermarks are needed?To handle:late events, out-of-order streams, event-time correctness
Source and Sink - Source: where data comes from (Kafka, Kinesis) - Sink: where results go (DB, S3, Elasticsearch)
Out-of-order events handling - Flink uses: event time, watermarks to correctly place late events into correct windows.
State allows Flink to do: running counts, session tracking, aggregations, pattern detection. Without state → only stateless filtering.
Flink scales by: partitioning streams (keyBy), parallel operator execution, distributed cluster (TaskManagers).
Backpressure happens when: downstream operator is slower than upstream - causing upstream buffers to fill and slow down ingestion.
Fault tolerance in Flink uses: checkpointing, state snapshots, restart strategies
Checkpointing periodically saves: operator state , source offsets to durable storage for recovery.
Savepoint vs Checkpoint - Checkpoint: automatic, for recovery - Savepoint: manual, for upgrades/migration.
Flink reads Kafka offsets as part of checkpoint → ensures consistent replay after failure.
what happens on restart - Flink:restores last checkpoint, restores operator state, resets Kafka offsets, resumes processing
A distributed snapshot is a globally consistent state of:all operators, all streams, all offsets taken at the same logical time.
Trade-offs of large state - Large state leads to:high memory usage, slow checkpointing, longer recovery time, increased storage cost
External system consistency issue: Even if Flink is exactly-once internally: external DB writes may still duplicate unless idempotent or transactional sinks are used.
Why Flink is true streaming: Unlike Spark micro-batching:Flink processes event-by-event, maintains continuous state, low latency (ms-level)


java example - 
DataStream<Event> stream = env.addSource(kafkaSource);

stream
  .keyBy(event -> event.userId)
  .window(TumblingProcessingTimeWindows.of(Time.seconds(10)))
  .sum("clickCount");

why Flink powerful - 
1. Exactly-once processing
         No duplicate processing (critical for payments/logs)
         done by checkpointing, distributed snapshots, failure recovery using failed state
         What gets stored in a checkpoint:
                  operator state (aggregations, counters, sessions)
                  Kafka offsets / source positions
                  window states
                  in-flight processing state
         sends snapshot to durable storage (usually S3/HDFS).this is a global consistent snapshot across all distributed operators
         Why “distributed” matters In Flink:
                  multiple nodes process different parts of stream
                  data is partitioned (keyed streams)
                  each operator runs independently
         now when task manger craches, flink fetches this stored snapshot from storage.
         Kafka offsets are restored, stream restarts from correct position
         Checkpoint ensures:
         ✔ event is either:
         included in snapshot OR not processed at all
         So after recovery: no duplicate processing, no missing updates
Flink achieves exactly-once semantics using periodic checkpointing, where distributed snapshots of operator state and source offsets are taken using barrier alignment. 
In case of failure, the system restores the last consistent snapshot and resumes processing from the saved offsets, ensuring no event is lost or processed twice.
2. True streaming (not micro-batch)
         Unlike Spark Streaming
3. Stateful + fault tolerant
         If system crashes → Flink restores state
Stateful processing means Flink remembers previous events (e.g., counts, sessions, aggregates) to compute future results.

Handling millions of events/sec in Flink
Techniques:
         1. Partitioning
         keyBy(userId / deviceId)
         parallel operators
         2. Horizontal scaling
         increase TaskManagers
         3. Backpressure handling
         buffer tuning
         async I/O
         4. Efficient state backend
         RocksDB state backend for large state
         5. Batch writes to sinks
         reduce DB pressure
         6. Use event filtering early
         reduce data volume upstream
Store & Query Flink State at Scale
         State storage options:
                  in-memory (fast, small state)
                  RocksDB (large state)
         Scaling strategies:
                  key partitioning
                  state sharding
                  incremental checkpoints
